\section{Lecture 9 -- Stable $\infty$-Categories}
Today truly marks the final day of foundations as we set out to define
stable $\infty$-categories. But first we want to discuss symmetric
monoidal $\infty$-categories and localisations.

\subsection{Symmetric Monoidality and Localisation}
Let $\cC$ and $\cD$ be presentable $\infty$-categories and suppose we
have a reflexive localisation
\[\begin{tikzcd} F:\cC\arrow[r,shift right]&{\cD:G}\arrow[l,
    shift right, hook']
  \end{tikzcd}\] i.e. such that $G$ is fully faithful and $\cD$ is
$\cC[S^{-1}]$ for some set $S\subset \cC_1$.
\begin{question}
  If $\cC^\otimes$ is a symmetric monoidal structure on $\cC$, when
  does it descend to $\cD$?
\end{question}
\begin{answer}
  If for every $x\xrightarrow{f}y\in S$ and for every $z\in \cC$ the
  corresponding map $x\otimes z\to y\otimes z$ is in $S$ then the
  adjunction $F$ is monoidal and $G$ is lax monoidal.
\end{answer}

\begin{example}
  Let consider $\cC=\Ab$ and $\cD=\Ab_p^{\wedge}$ and suppose $M,N\in
  \Ab$. Define $F(M)=M_p^{\wedge}$. Then define a symmetric monoidal
  structure on $\cD$ by $(M\otimes N)_p^{\wedge}:=(M_p^\wedge\otimes N_p^\wedge)$
\end{example}

